/* ============================================================
   The Sun & the Sword — Content  [SUBJECT: sunsword]
   An island where a curious kid travels back ~2,000 years and
   meets the most magnetic humans who ever lived. Story-first,
   then a difficulty-curved 6-question quiz. Honest about the
   brilliance AND the cost. Reads for a sharp ~13-year-old.

   ARCS (2026-06-20):
     1. "The Men Who Asked Why" — Socrates, Diogenes, Plato, Aristotle.
     2. "The Boy Who Wanted the World" — Philip, Alexander (rise, cost, the empire that vanished).
     3. "The King Who Wept" — Chandragupta & Chanakya, Ashoka's Kalinga, dharma & the edicts.
   Each arc: story-first lessons (6-Q curved quizzes) + an arc review + an argue-both-sides debate.
   Facts checked against standard history; dates are BCE.

   Data ships as a window global (file://-safe; no fetch).
   ============================================================ */

window.SUNSWORD = window.SUNSWORD || {};
SUNSWORD.CONTENT = { arcs: [], lessons: {}, intro: [] };

(function (C) {
  var L = C.lessons;
  function arc(o) { C.arcs.push(o); }
  function lesson(o) { L[o.id] = o; }

  /* ---------- HOME overview (what this island is) ---------- */
  C.intro = [
    { t: "lead", html: "Step off the boat and the year is not 2026. It is closer to <b>400 BCE</b>. The air smells of olive trees, sea salt, and woodsmoke. Somewhere down the hill, a barefoot old man is about to ask a powerful person a question they cannot answer — and change the world by doing it." },
    { t: "p", html: "This is an island of the most <b>magnetic humans who ever lived</b> — thinkers, conquerors, rebels, builders, and a few genuine villains. You will not memorize a list of dates. You will <i>meet</i> people. By the end you will understand something you didn’t before — about them, and quietly, about yourself." },
    { t: "keyidea", tag: "How it works", html: "Each lesson is a short, true story. <b>Read first</b> — the story earns your attention. Then take a quick 6-question quiz that gets a little harder as it goes. Finish an arc to earn its place in the <b>Hall of Names</b>." },
  ];

  /* ============================================================
     ARC 1 — THE MEN WHO ASKED WHY
     ============================================================ */
  arc({
    id: "askwhy",
    name: "The Men Who Asked Why",
    emoji: "🏛️",
    color: "#b07a32", color2: "#6d4a1f",
    blurb: "Four thinkers in one small city asked “How should a person live?” — and the questions outlived every king around them.",
    intro: "In one city — Athens — across about a hundred years, four men taught one another and argued with everyone. They built no empires. They left no armies. And yet 2,400 years later we still use their questions, their methods, even their jokes. This is where wisdom in the Western world starts arguing with itself.",
    overview: [
      { t: "p", html: "Picture a single chain of teachers and students: <b>Socrates</b> taught <b>Plato</b>, Plato taught <b>Aristotle</b>, and Aristotle tutored a teenager named <b>Alexander</b> who would go on to conquer the known world. Four links. One of the most important chains in history." },
      { t: "p", html: "And off to the side, refusing to join anyone’s school, a homeless troublemaker named <b>Diogenes</b> lived in a barrel and mocked them all — including the conqueror. You’ll like him." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "Seeker of Wisdom", emoji: "🦉" },
    lessons: ["socrates", "diogenes", "plato", "aristotle"],

    /* ---- arc review quiz (spans all four) ---- */
    review: [
      { q: "Who taught whom? Put the chain in the right direction.", type: "mc",
        options: ["Socrates → Plato → Aristotle", "Aristotle → Plato → Socrates", "Plato → Socrates → Aristotle", "They never met each other"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Socrates taught Plato, and Plato taught Aristotle — one of the most important teacher-student chains in history. Aristotle then tutored Alexander the Great." },
      { q: "Which of these four left behind <b>no written works of his own</b>?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Socrates", "Plato", "Aristotle", "All of them wrote books"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Socrates never wrote anything down. We only know him because his student Plato wrote about him." },
      { q: "Diogenes told the most powerful man alive to do what?", type: "mc",
        options: ["“Step out of my sunlight.”", "“Make me your general.”", "“Build me a palace.”", "“Teach me to fight.”"],
        answer: 0, explain: "When Alexander the Great offered him anything, Diogenes asked only that Alexander stop blocking his sun." },
      { q: "True or false: Plato’s “Allegory of the Cave” argues that most people mistake shadows for reality.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 0, explain: "True. In the Cave, prisoners think shadows on a wall are the whole world — Plato’s image for living without ever questioning what’s real." },
      { q: "Aristotle’s big method — the thing that makes him feel surprisingly modern — was to:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Observe the real world carefully and collect evidence", "Trust only what the gods revealed", "Refuse to write anything down", "Win arguments for money"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Aristotle observed and catalogued everything — animals, governments, the stars. That habit of gathering evidence is the seed of science." },
      { q: "All four men lived within a few generations in roughly the same place. Where?", type: "mc",
        options: ["In and around Athens, Greece", "In Rome, Italy", "In Alexandria, Egypt", "In Sparta"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Athens — a single small Greek city — was the home base for all four. Ideas, not size, made it a giant." },
      { q: "Here’s the hard one. What did Socrates mean by “I know that I am wise only in knowing that I know nothing”?", type: "mc",
        options: ["That admitting what you don’t know is the start of real wisdom", "That he was the smartest man alive", "That learning is pointless", "That nobody can ever know anything"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He wasn’t bragging or giving up — he meant that people who <i>think</i> they know everything stop learning. Knowing the limits of your knowledge is where wisdom begins." },
    ],

    /* ---- debate card ---- */
    debate: {
      id: "socrates-escape",
      tag: "Big question — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "Socrates was sentenced to death. His friends arranged an escape. Should he have run?",
      setup: "He could have slipped out of Athens and lived. Instead he stayed and drank the hemlock. Make the strongest case for <i>each</i> choice — that’s what great thinkers do.",
      a: { label: "He was right to stay", h: "Stay and accept it",
        body: "Socrates spent his whole life saying laws and justice matter more than staying comfortable. If he ran the moment a law hurt <i>him</i>, every lesson he ever taught would look like a lie. Dying for what you taught can be the loudest lesson of all." },
      b: { label: "He should have run", h: "Run and live",
        body: "The verdict was unjust — even many Athenians later regretted it. A living Socrates could have kept teaching for decades and done far more good. Refusing to flee an unfair punishment can be noble, or it can just be a waste of a brilliant mind." },
    },
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON 1 — SOCRATES ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "socrates", arc: "askwhy", n: 1, minutes: 15,
    title: "Socrates — The Man Who Knew Nothing",
    hook: "He wrote no books, won no battles, and owned almost nothing. Yet 2,400 years later, the way you argue in a debate, the way a good teacher pushes you with questions instead of answers — that’s <i>his</i>.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "A barefoot old man stops a confident young politician in the crowded <b>agora</b>. “You said you know what justice is,” he says, smiling. “Wonderful — I’ve been looking for someone who does. Teach me?” Ten minutes later, a crowd is laughing, and the young man realizes, in public, that he cannot actually explain the thing he was so sure about.",
        note: "Athens, around 410 BCE. The old man is Socrates, and this is the most dangerous thing in the city: a really good question." },
      { t: "p", html: "Picture the place for a moment, because the place is half the story. The agora was the beating heart of Athens — a wide open marketplace where people came to buy fish and olives, swap gossip, argue about politics, and show off. It was loud, sun-baked, and crowded. Into that swirl of important, busy people walked a man who looked like he owned nothing, because he very nearly did, and who treated a grand politician exactly the same way he treated a shoemaker: as someone who might, if pushed gently enough, have to admit he didn’t really know what he was talking about." },
      { t: "p", html: "Socrates (born about <b>470 BCE</b>) didn’t look like a hero. He was famously ugly, often shoeless, and didn’t care about money. His weapon was conversation. He’d ask someone a simple question — <i>What is courage? What is justice?</i> — and then gently ask more questions until their confident answer fell apart. We call this question-and-answer method, still used in classrooms and courtrooms today, the <b>Socratic method</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here is what made it so disarming: he never lectured. He never stood up and announced the right answer, partly because he insisted he didn’t have it. He just <i>asked</i>. ‘You say a brave man is one who stands his ground in battle. But what about a doctor who calmly stays in a plague city to heal the sick — is that not also courage? And what about a soldier who stands still out of pure stubbornness, with no idea why — is <i>that</i> brave?’ One small question after another, until the confident speaker discovered that the idea he’d been so sure of had holes in it he had simply never noticed." },
      { t: "p", html: "That is a stranger and more powerful thing than it sounds. Most people, then and now, walk around carrying beliefs they’ve never actually examined — opinions they absorbed from family, from friends, from the crowd — and they mistake the comfortable feeling of certainty for the harder thing called knowledge. Socrates’ whole life was a campaign against that comfortable feeling. He wanted people to <i>think</i>, even when thinking made them squirm." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The oracle’s riddle", html: "A friend asked the <b>oracle</b> at Delphi if anyone was wiser than Socrates. The priestess said no. Socrates was baffled — he felt he knew nothing. So he spent years questioning “wise” people to prove the oracle wrong… and discovered they only <i>thought</i> they were wise. That, he decided, was the difference: he at least knew what he didn’t know." },
      { t: "quote", html: "I know that I am wise only in knowing that I know nothing.", who: "Socrates (as written by Plato)" },
      { t: "p", html: "Sit with that sentence, because it’s easy to misread. He is not saying he’s stupid, and he is certainly not saying nothing can be known. He is saying something sharper: that the most dangerous person in any room is the one who is certain they already understand. Such a person has stopped looking. They’ve closed the door. The honest admission ‘I don’t actually know this yet’ is not weakness — it’s the exact moment real learning becomes possible, because now there’s room for something new to get in." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "A tool you can steal", html: "Next time you catch yourself absolutely sure about something — a person, a team, a fact ‘everybody knows’ — try the Socratic move on <i>yourself</i>. Ask: ‘How do I actually know that? What would change my mind?’ That single habit, used honestly, is most of what made a barefoot old man the most quoted thinker in history." },
      { t: "p", html: "This made him beloved by curious young people — and infuriating to powerful ones. Imagine being publicly out-thought by a shoeless old man, again and again. Athens had just lost a long, brutal war, people were frightened, and Socrates kept poking holes in everyone’s certainties." },
      { t: "p", html: "And the timing could not have been worse for him. A city that has just lost a war and feels afraid does not want to be told that its leaders don’t really understand justice. Frightened people crave certainty; they want someone to tell them everything will be fine and that the old answers still hold. Socrates offered the opposite — endless, patient, uncomfortable questions — and to a nervous, wounded city, that began to feel less like wisdom and more like a threat." },
      { t: "p", html: "In <b>399 BCE</b>, the city put him on trial. The charges: “corrupting the youth” and disrespecting the gods. Really, he was on trial for being annoying in a way that threatened powerful people. Offered a chance to apologize and stop, he refused — and even joked that the city should <i>reward</i> him instead." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about how much courage — or how much stubbornness, depending on your view — that took. He could have wept, begged, promised to keep quiet. Defendants did that all the time, and juries often softened. Instead he stood in front of the men who held his life in their hands and essentially said: I have spent my whole life trying to make this city wiser and better; if you understood what I was doing, you would thank me, not punish me. It was true. It was also exactly the kind of thing that gets a man condemned." },
      { t: "scene", html: "The jury votes. Guilty. The sentence: death by drinking <b>hemlock</b>, a slow poison. His friends bribe the guards and beg him to escape. He says no. To run from the law, he argues, would betray everything he ever taught. He drinks it calmly, still discussing big ideas with his friends, and dies." },
      { t: "p", html: "That last scene is one of the most famous deaths in all of history, and it’s worth understanding why his friends were so desperate and why he refused them. They had the bribes ready, the escape route planned; he could have lived out his years somewhere safe. But Socrates had spent decades arguing that a good life means living by your principles even when it costs you — <i>especially</i> when it costs you. To flee the moment a law turned against him would have made every word of that a lie. So he stayed, and turned even his final hours into one more calm conversation about the soul. (Whether he was right to stay is exactly the question waiting for you on this arc’s debate card.)" },
      { t: "aside", who: "Diogenes says", face: "barrel", html: "“They killed him for asking questions. Think about how good the questions must have been.”" },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why he still matters", html: "Socrates proved that <b>asking the right question</b> can be braver — and more powerful — than any answer. He’s why we say the goal of learning isn’t to <i>sound</i> smart, but to find out what you actually don’t understand yet." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What was Socrates’ main “weapon”?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Asking people questions", "A sword", "His great wealth", "An army"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Conversation. He asked questions until a person’s confident answer fell apart — the “Socratic method.”" },
      { q: "True or false: Socrates wrote many famous books.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 1, explain: "False — he never wrote anything. We know him only because students like Plato wrote about him." },
      { q: "The oracle at Delphi said no one was wiser than Socrates. Why did that confuse him?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He felt he knew nothing", "He’d never heard of the oracle", "He thought he was the wisest already", "He couldn’t travel to Delphi"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He genuinely believed he knew almost nothing — so the oracle’s answer sent him on a years-long quest to understand it." },
      { q: "What did Socrates conclude was his one real advantage over the “wise” people he questioned?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He knew what he didn’t know", "He was richer", "He was a better fighter", "He could vote and they couldn’t"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Others only <i>thought</i> they were wise. Socrates at least knew the limits of his own knowledge — and kept learning." },
      { q: "Socrates was really put on trial because he:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Embarrassed powerful people by exposing their weak ideas", "Stole money from the city", "Led a rebel army", "Refused to fight in any war"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The official charges were vague. The real problem: he kept publicly poking holes in powerful people’s certainties, in a frightened city." },
      { q: "The hardest one: his choice to drink the hemlock instead of escaping shows that he believed —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Living by your principles matters more than just staying alive", "The law is always correct", "Death didn’t frighten anyone in Athens", "His friends had betrayed him"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He’d taught for years that justice and principle come first. Fleeing would have made his whole life’s teaching look fake — so he stayed. (You can disagree — that’s the debate card!)" },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON 2 — DIOGENES ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "diogenes", arc: "askwhy", n: 2, minutes: 15,
    title: "Diogenes — The Dog in the Barrel",
    hook: "He lived in a barrel, owned a single cup until he threw it away, and insulted the most powerful man on earth to his face. He may be the most fearless person in this whole island.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "The most powerful man alive — <b>Alexander the Great</b>, who has conquered most of the known world — hears about a famous wise man and goes to meet him. He finds Diogenes lying in the dirt, sunbathing beside his barrel. “I am Alexander,” he says. “Ask me for anything you want.” Diogenes squints up at him and replies: “Yes — could you step out of my sunlight?”",
        note: "Corinth, around 336 BCE. Alexander’s soldiers wait for the order to punish the insult. It never comes." },
      { t: "p", html: "Hold that picture in your mind, because almost nothing about it makes ordinary sense. Here is a young king at the dizzy height of his fame, surrounded by armed guards, offering to grant any wish a person could dream up — palaces, gold, an army, a kingdom. And here is a filthy, half-naked old man who responds as though a stranger had merely wandered in front of the TV. He doesn’t want what Alexander is offering. He doesn’t even want to sit up. The only thing the conqueror has that Diogenes values is the sunshine he’s accidentally blocking." },
      { t: "p", html: "Diogenes (about <b>412–323 BCE</b>) belonged to a group called the <b>Cynics</b> — the word comes from the Greek for “dog,” and he wore it proudly, calling himself “Diogenes the Dog.” His big idea was radical: almost everything people chase — money, fame, fancy houses, status — is a cage. True freedom is needing <i>almost nothing</i>." },
      { t: "p", html: "It helps to understand <i>why</i> a person would choose to live this way on purpose. Diogenes looked around at the busy, ambitious people of his world and saw them all working themselves ragged — for finer clothes, bigger houses, important titles, the approval of neighbors — and he asked a brutal question: who is really the master here, the person or the stuff? If you <i>need</i> the fancy house to feel okay, then the house owns you. If you’d be crushed to lose your status, then your status is your jailer. The only person truly free, he decided, is the one who can lose almost everything and shrug, because he wanted almost nothing in the first place." },
      { t: "p", html: "So he lived it, completely. He made his home in a large ceramic storage jar (history nicknamed it his “barrel”). He owned a wooden cup — until he saw a child drink from cupped hands and threw the cup away, annoyed a child had out-simplified him. He begged for food and said outrageous things in public to wake people up." },
      { t: "p", html: "He was, to be honest, often deliberately rude and shocking, and that was the point — he was a kind of one-man protest against politeness he thought was fake. If a rich man hosted a fancy dinner full of show-offs, Diogenes might do something gross or insulting just to puncture the whole performance, to remind everyone that underneath the silk robes they were all just animals who needed food and sleep like anybody else. You don’t have to admire every stunt to see the nerve underneath it: he genuinely did not care what powerful people thought of him, and almost nobody can say that honestly." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The man with the lamp", html: "Diogenes once walked through the busy market in <b>daylight</b> holding a lit lamp. People asked what he was doing. “I’m looking for an honest person,” he said — implying he hadn’t found one yet. It was performance art, 2,300 years before that was a phrase." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "The wink inside the stunts", html: "Notice that Diogenes almost never argued the way Socrates did, with careful questions. He argued with <i>actions</i> — a lamp in daylight, a thrown-away cup, a barrel for a house. Each was a tiny piece of theater designed to make a busy crowd stop and think for one second about how they actually live. He’s proof that a sharp idea can be delivered as a joke and land just as hard." },
      { t: "p", html: "Back to Alexander. After the sunlight insult, Alexander’s soldiers expected fury. Instead Alexander reportedly turned to them and said something extraordinary about a homeless man who had just mocked him —" },
      { t: "quote", html: "If I were not Alexander, I would wish to be Diogenes.", who: "Alexander the Great" },
      { t: "p", html: "Why would the most powerful man envy a beggar? Because Alexander spent his whole life wanting <i>more</i> — more land, more glory — and could never stop. Diogenes wanted <i>nothing</i>, and so nobody on earth had any power over him. There’s a real question hiding in that joke: who was actually freer?" },
      { t: "p", html: "This is the quiet trap that Diogenes spotted and Alexander couldn’t escape, and it’s worth carrying with you through this whole island. A person who always wants more can never arrive — there is always a richer man, a bigger conquest, a higher rung. Their hunger is the leash, and they hold the other end themselves. A person who has trained themselves to want very little has, in a strange way, already won: there is nothing left to take from them, nothing left to fear losing. The barrel was empty, but the man inside it slept soundly. The conqueror, with the whole world, often could not." },
      { t: "p", html: "Now, it would be easy to romanticize all this, and it’s worth being honest: most people would not actually want to live in a jar, and Diogenes could be obnoxious, dirty, and impossible to be around. He’s not really a how-to guide for life. He’s something more useful — a question with legs. Every generation drowns in things ‘everybody’ chases: the right clothes, the right gadget, the right number of followers, the right kind of fame. Diogenes is the voice at the edge of the crowd asking, ‘Wait — do you actually want this, or have you just been told to want it?’ You don’t have to throw away your cup. You only have to be able to answer him honestly." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that connects him straight back to Socrates, the man from your last lesson. Socrates questioned people’s <i>ideas</i> until their certainties cracked; Diogenes questioned people’s whole <i>way of living</i> until their assumptions looked ridiculous. Different methods, same target: the unexamined life, lived on autopilot, doing what everyone else does because everyone else does it. Athens managed to produce, within a few decades, both the gentlest questioner and the rudest one — and between them they made it almost impossible for a thoughtful person to ever again say ‘that’s just how things are’ without flinching a little." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why he still matters", html: "Diogenes is the island’s built-in troublemaker — the voice that asks every king and every trend, “But <i>why</i> do you want that?” He’s a reminder that you can question what everyone around you assumes is obviously good." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Where did Diogenes famously live?", type: "mc",
        options: ["In a large barrel/jar", "In a palace", "On a warship", "In a temple"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He made his home in a big ceramic storage jar — history nicknamed it his “barrel” — to prove he needed almost nothing." },
      { q: "When Alexander the Great offered him anything, Diogenes asked him to:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Step out of his sunlight", "Give him gold", "Make him a king", "Build him a house"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He wanted nothing Alexander could give — only that Alexander stop blocking the sun." },
      { q: "Diogenes called himself a Cynic. What does that word come from?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The Greek word for “dog”", "The Greek word for “king”", "The name of his city", "A type of weapon"],
        answer: 0, explain: "“Cynic” comes from the Greek for “dog.” Diogenes embraced it and called himself “Diogenes the Dog.”" },
      { q: "Why did Diogenes throw away his only cup?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He saw a child drink from cupped hands and realized he didn’t even need the cup", "It was broken", "Someone stole a better one for him", "He traded it for food"],
        answer: 0, explain: "A child drinking from bare hands out-simplified him — so he ditched the cup. For Diogenes, owning less meant being freer." },
      { q: "Alexander said, “If I were not Alexander, I would wish to be Diogenes.” What’s the deeper point?", type: "mc",
        options: ["A person who needs nothing can’t be controlled by anyone", "Diogenes was secretly rich", "Alexander wanted to live in a barrel", "Beggars make the best generals"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Alexander always wanted more and could be tempted or threatened. Diogenes wanted nothing — so no one had power over him. That freedom is what Alexander envied." },
      { q: "The trickiest one: the lamp-in-daylight stunt was Diogenes’ way of saying —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Honest people are so rare he had to go ‘searching’ for one", "He was afraid of the dark", "The market was poorly lit", "He had lost something valuable"],
        answer: 0, explain: "It was a piece of street theater: carrying a lamp in broad daylight to ‘search’ for an honest person was a sharp, funny way to criticize how people actually behaved." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON 3 — PLATO ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "plato", arc: "askwhy", n: 3, minutes: 15,
    title: "Plato — The Student Who Wrote It All Down",
    hook: "Socrates left no books — so the whole world might have forgotten him. One student made sure that didn’t happen, and then built ideas so big we’re still arguing about them.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "A young man with broad shoulders — his wrestling coach nicknamed him “Plato,” meaning “broad” — watches his teacher Socrates drink the hemlock and die. He is devastated, and furious at the city that did it. He makes a decision: the world will <b>not</b> forget Socrates. He will write the conversations down.",
        note: "Athens, 399 BCE. Plato is about 28. He will spend the rest of his life turning his teacher’s questions into books." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s worth pausing on how close the world came to losing Socrates entirely. A man who writes nothing down depends completely on memory — and memory dies with the people who hold it. Within a generation or two, the brilliant old questioner of the agora could have faded into a half-remembered rumor, a name with no ideas attached. That he didn’t — that we can still read his conversations today — is almost entirely down to one grieving, furious student who refused to let that happen." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Plato</b> (about <b>428–348 BCE</b>) wrote his books as <i>dialogues</i> — scripts of people arguing, almost always with Socrates as the star asking the questions. It’s a brilliant trick: instead of lecturing you, he makes you watch a debate and decide for yourself. Because of Plato, a man who never wrote a word became one of the most quoted humans in history." },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about what a clever choice the dialogue form was. Plato could easily have written a normal book — ‘Here is what I, Plato, believe about justice, in twelve points.’ Instead he wrote scenes: real-feeling people sitting at dinner or walking through town, disagreeing, getting confused, catching one another in contradictions. Reading it feels less like being taught and more like eavesdropping on the smartest conversation in the room. It pulls you in and makes you do the thinking yourself — which is, of course, exactly what Socrates always wanted from people." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a puzzle for historians buried in all this, and it’s a fascinating one. Because Socrates wrote nothing and Plato wrote so much, we can’t always tell where the teacher ends and the student begins. When the character ‘Socrates’ in a dialogue makes a brilliant point, is that the real Socrates being faithfully remembered — or Plato putting his own bigger ideas into his beloved teacher’s mouth? Probably both, blended together so finely that no one can fully separate them. The two men are tangled forever, which is its own kind of memorial." },
      { t: "p", html: "Then Plato did something that would echo for 2,400 years: around <b>387 BCE</b> he founded a school called the <b>Academy</b> — the original. (Every “academy” and “academic” since is named after his.) Students came from all over the Greek world to think there. One of them, a sharp teenager named Aristotle, is the star of your next lesson." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Plato’s most famous image — the Cave", html: "Imagine prisoners chained in a cave their whole lives, facing a blank wall. Behind them, a fire casts <b>shadows</b> of things passing by. The shadows are all they’ve ever seen, so they believe shadows are the whole world. Now imagine one prisoner is freed, walks outside, and sees the real sun for the first time. That blinding, beautiful shock — Plato said — is what learning the truth feels like." },
      { t: "p", html: "Let the image really sink in, because Plato packed several ideas into it at once. First: the prisoners aren’t stupid — they’re reasoning perfectly well about the only thing they’ve ever been shown. Given nothing but shadows, of course they conclude the world is made of shadows. The problem isn’t their thinking; it’s the narrowness of what they’ve been allowed to see. Second: when the freed prisoner first steps into the sunlight, it <i>hurts</i>. The truth doesn’t arrive gently. Real understanding can be dazzling and disorienting, and many people, given the chance, would rather scurry back to the comfortable dark." },
      { t: "p", html: "The Cave is Plato’s warning: most people go through life mistaking <i>shadows</i> — rumors, appearances, what everybody assumes — for reality, and they get angry at anyone who tries to drag them into the light. (Sound like anyone you know? It sounds a lot like what happened to Socrates.)" },
      { t: "p", html: "And here is the saddest, sharpest part of the story. In Plato’s telling, the freed prisoner doesn’t just walk away happy. He feels he has to go <i>back</i> into the cave to free the others — and when he does, blinking and stumbling because his eyes are no longer used to the dark, the prisoners think the outside ruined him. They laugh. They want nothing to do with his strange talk of a sun. If anyone tried to drag <i>them</i> out, the story warns, they might even kill him. Plato had just watched his own city do exactly that to the kindest questioner it ever had. The Cave is grief turned into a picture." },
      { t: "fact", label: "Philosopher-kings", html: "Plato had a bold, controversial idea about government: cities should be ruled by the wisest, best-trained thinkers — “philosopher-kings” — not by whoever is richest or most popular. Critics have argued for centuries that this is either deep wisdom or a recipe for bossy know-it-alls. What do <i>you</i> think?" },
      { t: "p", html: "You can feel where this idea came from, too. Plato had watched a popular vote in a democracy condemn the wisest man he knew to death. Naturally he grew suspicious of letting the loudest or most popular voice decide everything — surely, he thought, the people best at thinking should be the ones in charge. It’s a tempting argument. But notice the trapdoor under it: <i>who decides</i> which people are the wise ones? Hand that judgment to the wrong group and ‘rule by the wise’ quietly becomes ‘rule by whoever managed to call themselves wise.’ Twenty-four centuries later, we’re still arguing about it — which is a sign Plato found a genuinely hard problem, not an easy one." },
      { t: "p", html: "Plato could be a bit of a dreamer — he believed in a perfect, invisible world of ideal “Forms” behind the messy real one. His student Aristotle would politely, stubbornly disagree, and walk in the opposite direction. That disagreement basically launched 2,000 years of philosophy." },
      { t: "p", html: "Don’t let the word ‘dreamer’ sound like an insult, though — Plato’s big swings are exactly why he still matters. Lots of people can poke holes in ideas; very few dare to imagine, in detail, how the whole world might fit together — what reality really is, how a perfect society might run, what makes a life good. Plato dared. Some of his answers look strange to us now, and his own brilliant student spent a lifetime arguing against the biggest one. But he raised the questions so clearly, and chased them so far, that everyone who came after has been answering him in one way or another. There’s an old line that all of Western philosophy is just ‘footnotes to Plato.’ It’s an exaggeration — but you can see why someone said it." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "Why is Plato so important to the story of Socrates?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He wrote down Socrates’ conversations so they survived", "He was Socrates’ jailer", "He paid for Socrates’ trial", "He invented the hemlock"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Socrates wrote nothing. Plato recorded his teacher’s ideas as written dialogues — which is the main reason we still know Socrates today." },
      { q: "The school Plato founded was called the:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Academy", "Lyceum", "Senate", "Colosseum"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The Academy, founded around 387 BCE — the original, which every later “academy” is named after." },
      { q: "Plato wrote his works as ‘dialogues.’ What does that mean?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Scripts of people arguing out a question", "Long lists of dates", "Poems about war", "Secret coded messages"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Dialogues are written debates. Instead of lecturing, Plato lets you watch characters argue and decide for yourself." },
      { q: "In the Allegory of the Cave, the shadows on the wall stand for:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Appearances people mistake for the whole truth", "Real, perfect knowledge", "The gods", "Money"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The chained prisoners think shadows are reality. Plato’s point: most people mistake appearances for truth — until something drags them into the light." },
      { q: "How does the Cave connect to what happened to Socrates?", type: "mc",
        options: ["People often resent the person trying to show them an uncomfortable truth", "It explains how hemlock works", "It proves the gods were real", "It shows Athens won the war"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The freed prisoner who returns to free the others is mocked — just as Athens silenced Socrates for challenging its comfortable certainties." },
      { q: "Trickiest: Plato’s idea of ‘philosopher-kings’ is debated because —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Ruling by ‘the wisest’ sounds great until you ask who decides who’s wisest", "No one understood what he meant", "He never actually wrote it down", "It was illegal in Athens"],
        answer: 0, explain: "It’s a genuine dilemma: rule by the wise <i>could</i> be ideal, but it can also become rule by self-appointed know-it-alls. Great thinkers still argue both sides." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON 4 — ARISTOTLE ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "aristotle", arc: "askwhy", n: 4, minutes: 15,
    title: "Aristotle — The Man Who Wanted to Know Everything",
    hook: "Socrates asked questions. Plato dreamed of a perfect world. Aristotle did something different and a little bit magical: he went outside and started <i>counting things</i>. That habit became science.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "A man crouches at the edge of a lagoon, sleeves wet, carefully cutting open a fish to see how it’s built inside. Around him, students take notes on hundreds of animals. He is one of the most famous thinkers alive, and he is happily covered in fish guts, because he has decided the way to understand the world is to <b>look at it</b>.",
        note: "The island of Lesbos, around 344 BCE. This is Aristotle — and this muddy curiosity is the ancestor of every science class you’ll ever take." },
      { t: "p", html: "To feel how strange and new this was, picture what the great thinkers before him had mostly done: they sat, and they reasoned. They built grand ideas about the world out of pure thought, the way you might solve a math problem in your head. Aristotle respected all that — he was a magnificent reasoner himself — but he added a step nobody had taken so seriously before. He went out and <i>checked</i>. He waded into lagoons. He dissected creatures. He asked beekeepers and fishermen what they’d actually seen. The truth, he decided, was not only in your head; a great deal of it was lying around in the real world, waiting for someone patient enough to look." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Aristotle</b> (<b>384–322 BCE</b>) came from a northern town called Stagira and joined Plato’s Academy as a teenager, studying there for about 20 years. He loved Plato — but he disagreed with him on something huge. Plato looked <i>up</i>, toward a perfect invisible world of ideal Forms. Aristotle looked <i>down and around</i>, at the actual world, and said: the truth is right here, if we observe it carefully enough." },
      { t: "p", html: "That disagreement is more touching than it first sounds, because Aristotle clearly adored his teacher. Twenty years is a long time to study at someone’s side. To then say, gently but firmly, ‘I think you’ve got the most important thing backwards’ takes a particular kind of courage and a particular kind of honesty. There’s a saying often attached to him that captures it: he loved Plato dearly, but he loved the truth more. That single sentence is most of what science is — the willingness to follow the evidence even when it walks you away from people you respect." },
      { t: "p", html: "So he observed <i>everything</i>. He studied animals, plants, weather, the stars, poetry, friendship, and government — and he basically invented the idea of <b>logic</b>, the rules for telling a good argument from a sneaky one. No human before him had tried to organize <i>all</i> of human knowledge. He came closer than anyone had ever come." },
      { t: "p", html: "Try to grasp the sheer <i>scale</i> of that ambition, because it’s almost unimaginable. We live in a world that splits knowledge into hundreds of subjects — biology, physics, ethics, drama, politics, astronomy — and each has thousands of specialists who spend whole careers on one tiny corner. Aristotle tried to map <i>all of it</i>, by himself, from scratch, with no internet, no library catalog, no earlier system to copy. He didn’t just study these subjects; in many cases he was the first person to draw the lines that turned a heap of observations <i>into</i> a subject. Whole fields begin with him because there was simply no one there before him." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "What ‘logic’ gave us", html: "Aristotle’s gift of logic was a set of rules for spotting whether an argument actually holds together — the difference between a real proof and a sneaky trick that just <i>sounds</i> convincing. Every time you catch someone changing the subject, or notice that a conclusion doesn’t really follow from the reasons given, you’re using tools he was among the very first to write down. It’s mental self-defense, 2,300 years old." },
      { t: "fact", label: "He tutored a future conqueror", html: "Around 343 BCE, a king hired Aristotle to tutor his 13-year-old son. The boy was <b>Alexander</b> — soon to be Alexander the Great. So the chain is complete: Socrates taught Plato, Plato taught Aristotle, and Aristotle taught the teenager who would conquer the known world. Four links, one little corner of Greece." },
      { t: "order", title: "Line up the chain of teachers", sub: "Drag these into the order they happened — earliest at the top.",
        items: [ { yr: "~399 BCE", label: "Socrates is put on trial and dies" },
                 { yr: "~387 BCE", label: "Plato founds the Academy" },
                 { yr: "~343 BCE", label: "Aristotle becomes Alexander’s tutor" },
                 { yr: "~335 BCE", label: "Aristotle founds his own school, the Lyceum" } ] },
      { t: "p", html: "Aristotle also gave famously practical advice about how to live. His idea of the <b>“golden mean”</b> says the best path usually sits <i>between</i> two extremes: courage is the mean between cowardice and recklessness; generosity sits between stinginess and showing off. Not flashy — but you can actually use it tomorrow." },
      { t: "p", html: "What’s lovely about the golden mean is how grown-up it is. It refuses the easy promise that there’s one simple rule for being good — ‘always be bold!’ or ‘always be generous!’ Aristotle noticed that nearly every good quality turns bad if you take it too far. Confidence is wonderful until it tips into arrogance; carefulness is wise until it curdles into never daring anything at all. The skill of living well, he taught, isn’t picking a slogan and obeying it forever — it’s the constant, alert work of finding the right amount, for this person, in this situation, right now. That’s harder than a slogan, and far more true to how real life actually feels." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here’s the honest part. Aristotle was so respected that for nearly <b>2,000 years</b> people treated his word as final — even when he was wrong. He thought heavier objects fall faster than light ones (they don’t). Because everyone trusted him, that mistake stuck around for centuries until scientists finally <i>tested</i> it. The lesson cuts against him beautifully: even the greatest mind should be checked against evidence — which is exactly what Aristotle himself would have wanted." },
      { t: "p", html: "There is a real irony worth sitting with here. The man who taught the world to <i>check things against evidence</i> became so famous that, for centuries, people stopped checking <i>him</i>. His name carried so much weight that ‘Aristotle said so’ was treated as the end of an argument rather than the beginning of one — the exact opposite of everything he stood for. The cure, when it finally came, was simply someone willing to do what Aristotle himself had done at that lagoon: stop trusting the famous answer and go test it for yourself. The student who corrects the master is keeping faith with the master’s real lesson, not betraying it." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why he still matters", html: "Aristotle turned curiosity into a <b>method</b>: observe, gather evidence, organize, reason carefully. Every time you do an experiment or ask “how do we actually <i>know</i> that?”, you’re standing on a habit he started by the side of a lagoon." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What made Aristotle’s approach feel so modern?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He observed the real world and gathered evidence", "He refused to study nature", "He only trusted dreams", "He never taught anyone"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He looked closely at the actual world — animals, weather, governments — and collected evidence. That habit is the root of science." },
      { q: "Aristotle studied at which school as a young man?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Plato’s Academy", "The Lyceum", "The Roman Senate", "Sparta’s war camp"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He joined Plato’s Academy as a teenager and stayed about 20 years before starting his own school later." },
      { q: "Famous teenager Aristotle tutored — who was it?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Alexander the Great", "Socrates", "Julius Caesar", "Diogenes"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Aristotle tutored the young Alexander, completing the chain: Socrates → Plato → Aristotle → Alexander." },
      { q: "Aristotle and Plato disagreed about something big. What?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Whether truth is found by observing the real world or by reasoning toward a perfect invisible one", "Whether Socrates existed", "Who should win a wrestling match", "Whether to write in Greek"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Plato looked ‘up’ to ideal Forms; Aristotle looked ‘down and around’ at the real world. That split shaped 2,000 years of thought." },
      { q: "What is Aristotle’s ‘golden mean’?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The good choice usually sits between two extremes", "A rule for melting gold", "A way to win any argument", "The center of the Academy"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Courage sits between cowardice and recklessness; generosity between stinginess and showing off. Balance, not extremes." },
      { q: "The deepest one: Aristotle being wrong about falling objects — yet believed for centuries — teaches us that —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Even a brilliant authority should be tested against evidence", "Aristotle knew nothing", "Heavy objects really do fall faster", "We should never trust scientists"],
        answer: 0, explain: "People trusted his authority so much they didn’t test the claim for ~2,000 years. The fix — checking ideas against evidence — is the very method Aristotle championed." },
    ],
  });

  /* ============================================================
     ARC 2 — THE BOY WHO WANTED THE WORLD  (Alexander)
     ============================================================ */
  arc({
    id: "alexander",
    name: "The Boy Who Wanted the World",
    emoji: "⚔️",
    color: "#b5892f", color2: "#7a5618",
    blurb: "A 20-year-old inherited an army and a dream, never lost a battle, and conquered the largest empire the world had ever seen — then died at 32 with nothing left to want.",
    intro: "Remember the teenager Aristotle tutored? This is his arc. Alexander of Macedon took the war machine his father built and pointed it at the entire known world — and it worked. He is dazzling and dangerous in equal measure, and the honest way to meet him is to admire the genius and count the cost at the same time.",
    overview: [
      { t: "p", html: "In just over a decade, Alexander marched an army from Greece to the edge of India, toppled the mightiest empire on earth, founded cities, and changed which languages, gods, and ideas spread across three continents. He genuinely <b>never lost a battle</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "But greatness and wreckage often shared the same person. He burned a capital, leveled a rebel city, killed a friend in a drunken rage, and drove his exhausted men to the breaking point chasing <i>more</i>. Both things are true. Hold them together — that’s the whole skill this island is teaching you." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "Bearer of the Sword", emoji: "⚔️" },
    lessons: ["philip", "alexrise", "alexcost", "alexempire"],

    review: [
      { q: "What weapon let the Macedonian phalanx strike before the enemy could reach it?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The sarissa — an extra-long pike", "A short dagger", "The longbow", "A catapult each soldier carried"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The sarissa was a pike up to ~5–6 metres long. A wall of them out-reached ordinary spears, so the enemy was hit before they could close in." },
      { q: "Who built the army and the kingdom that Alexander inherited?", type: "mc",
        options: ["His father, Philip II", "His tutor, Aristotle", "Diogenes", "King Darius"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Philip II turned little Macedon into a military superpower. Alexander inherited a finished machine — then drove it further than Philip ever dreamed." },
      { q: "True or false: Alexander lost several major battles but won the war anyway.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 1, explain: "False — across his whole career he never lost a major battle. That unbroken record is a huge part of his legend." },
      { q: "Which empire did Alexander conquer, defeating its king Darius III?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The Persian Empire", "The Roman Empire", "The Maurya Empire", "Carthage"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He toppled the vast Persian Empire — the superpower of the age — in a series of battles against King Darius III." },
      { q: "Why did Alexander’s conquests finally stop?", type: "mc",
        options: ["His own exhausted soldiers refused to march any farther", "He ran out of money", "He was defeated in India", "Aristotle ordered him home"],
        answer: 0, explain: "In India his loyal army had had enough — they refused to go on. The undefeated conqueror was stopped not by an enemy, but by his own men." },
      { q: "What happened to Alexander’s empire after he died at 32?", type: "mc",
        options: ["His generals fought over it and split it into pieces", "His son ruled it peacefully", "It became a republic", "Persia took it all back at once"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He left no clear heir, so his generals — the ‘Successors’ — carved the empire into rival kingdoms and fought for decades." },
      { q: "The hard one: historians say Alexander ‘won the world and lost himself.’ The best meaning is —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Endless conquest gave him everything except a reason to stop", "He literally got lost on a map", "He forgot how to fight", "He gave all his land away"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He could conquer anything but never feel finished. A life built only on wanting <i>more</i> has no endpoint — which is its own kind of trap, and the quiet warning inside his dazzling story." },
    ],

    debate: {
      id: "alex-great",
      tag: "Big question — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "We call him Alexander ‘the Great.’ Does he deserve the title?",
      setup: "He was a military genius who spread ideas across the world — and he also destroyed cities and killed thousands chasing glory. Make the strongest case for <i>each</i> side. ‘Great’ can mean ‘impressive’ or it can mean ‘good’ — notice which one you’re arguing.",
      a: { label: "Yes — he earned ‘Great’", h: "Greatness as achievement",
        body: "He did things no one had done: never lost a battle, united three continents, and spread Greek learning so widely it shaped the world for centuries. By the measure of sheer achievement and daring, almost no one compares." },
      b: { label: "No — ‘Great’ is too kind", h: "Count the cost",
        body: "Tens of thousands died for one man’s hunger for glory. He burned Persepolis and erased Thebes. ‘Great’ makes conquest sound noble — maybe we should reserve our highest word for people who <i>built</i> more than they destroyed." },
    },
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — PHILIP & THE WAR MACHINE ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "philip", arc: "alexander", n: 1, minutes: 15,
    title: "Philip’s War Machine",
    hook: "Before there was Alexander the Great, there was a one-eyed king who turned a poor, mocked little kingdom into the deadliest army on earth — and then handed it to his son.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "A council of polished Greek cities is laughing at Macedon — rough northern horse-country they barely consider properly Greek. They will not be laughing for long. Their new king has spent years as a hostage abroad, watching the best armies of the age, taking notes. He has come home with a plan to out-drill, out-reach, and out-think every one of them.",
        note: "Macedon, around 359 BCE. The new king is Philip II — and he is about to invent a way of fighting that his son will use to conquer the world." },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice the detail that everyone skips: Philip learned his craft as a <i>hostage</i>. As a young man he was held in another city as a kind of human guarantee of his kingdom’s good behavior — a common, humiliating arrangement back then. A lesser person would have spent those years sulking. Philip spent them studying. He watched how the most advanced armies of the day trained, marched, and fought, and he quietly filed it all away. When he finally came home to a weak, mocked little kingdom, he didn’t arrive empty-handed — he arrived with an education in war that none of his laughing neighbors knew he had." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Philip II</b> (382–336 BCE) was a brilliant organizer. His signature invention was the <b>sarissa</b>: a pike up to five or six metres long — far longer than a normal spear. He trained his soldiers to stand shoulder to shoulder in a deep block called a <b>phalanx</b>, sarissas leveled, so the enemy ran into a hedge of points and was struck before they could land a single blow." },
      { t: "p", html: "The genius of the sarissa is almost embarrassingly simple once you see it: in a fight between two spear-walls, the side with the <i>longer</i> spears wins, because they can stab the enemy while the enemy is still a step too far away to stab back. A Macedonian soldier could strike a man who literally could not reach him. Multiply that small, deadly advantage across a whole battlefield, thousands of points deep, and you have a wall of death that ordinary infantry simply could not get close to. It wasn’t magic. It was an idea, sharpened and repeated until it became overwhelming." },
      { t: "p", html: "But the pike was only half of it. Philip drilled his men relentlessly until they could move that bristling wall like one body, and he paired it with fast, hard-hitting cavalry on the wings. Phalanx pins the enemy in front; horsemen smash them from the side. It was less an army than a machine — and Philip built it from a kingdom everyone had written off." },
      { t: "p", html: "And ‘machine’ is exactly the right word, because the secret ingredient wasn’t any single weapon — it was <b>drill</b>. A clever idea on paper is worthless if a frightened, tired soldier can’t carry it out in the chaos of battle. So Philip made his men march and wheel and re-form, over and over, in heat and rain, until moving in perfect formation became as automatic as breathing. That endless, boring practice is what turned a crowd of farmers into a single thinking weapon. It’s a quiet lesson the flashy stories often miss: behind almost every ‘genius’ victory sits a mountain of unglamorous, repeated practice." },
      { t: "fact", label: "He led from the front", html: "Philip didn’t rule from a safe palace. He fought beside his men and collected the scars to prove it — including a wound that cost him an <b>eye</b>. Soldiers will follow a king who bleeds with them, and they followed Philip anywhere." },
      { t: "p", html: "That last point matters more than it looks. An army is not just weapons and formations; it’s thousands of human beings deciding, in a terrifying moment, whether to hold the line or run. Soldiers will risk everything for a leader they believe shares their danger — and they’ll quietly give up for one they suspect is hiding safely in the rear. By bleeding alongside his men, Philip bought a loyalty no amount of money could purchase. His son would inherit that lesson too, and use it to lead men to the ends of the earth." },
      { t: "p", html: "Philip’s queen was the fierce, formidable <b>Olympias</b>, and their son was <b>Alexander</b>. Philip gave that son two priceless gifts: the finest army in the world, and the finest teacher in the world — he hired <b>Aristotle</b> himself to tutor the boy. (Yes — that Aristotle, from your last arc. The chain connects.)" },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s worth saying plainly that Philip didn’t build all this just to defend his little kingdom. He had a grand ambition of his own: to unite the quarrelsome Greek cities under his leadership and then turn that combined power eastward against the mighty Persian empire. He had, in other words, already dreamed the dream his son would later make famous — and he had already built the tool to chase it. Alexander’s legend can make it sound as if the whole adventure sprang from one young genius. The truth is that the plan, the army, and the direction were largely waiting for him, handed down like a family inheritance." },
      { t: "scene", html: "At a grand royal wedding in 336 BCE, surrounded by guards and guests, Philip is suddenly struck down by an assassin and killed. In an instant, the man who built the machine is gone — and a 20-year-old inherits the most dangerous army on earth.",
        note: "Who was really behind it has been argued for 2,300 years. What’s certain: the throne, and the army, now belong to Alexander." },
      { t: "p", html: "Spare a thought for the cruelty of that timing. Philip had spent his whole life turning a mocked backwater into a superpower, and he died right at the threshold of the great campaign he’d been preparing for — never seeing whether his machine could actually conquer Persia. The glory he had built the road to went almost entirely to the son who walked it. History does that often: the person who lays the foundation is forgotten, while the person who happens to be standing on it when the building finishes gets remembered as the genius. It isn’t fair. It is, however, worth noticing, so you can give the quiet builders their due — the teachers, the parents, the founders who do the patient groundwork that someone else gets to finish in a blaze of glory." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why this matters", html: "Alexander is famous, but he didn’t start from nothing — he inherited a finished weapon. It’s a useful, unglamorous truth: the most dazzling success usually stands on a foundation someone <i>else</i> built first. Philip is that someone." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What was the sarissa?", type: "mc",
        options: ["An extra-long pike", "A war horse", "A type of shield", "A siege tower"],
        answer: 0, explain: "A pike up to five or six metres long — much longer than a normal spear, so the phalanx struck first." },
      { q: "Philip arranged his pike-men in a deep block called a:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Phalanx", "Legion", "Galley", "Caravan"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The phalanx: soldiers shoulder to shoulder, sarissas leveled into a hedge of points." },
      { q: "True or false: Philip ruled safely from his palace and never risked himself in battle.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 1, explain: "False — he fought at the front and even lost an eye in combat. His men followed him because he bled with them." },
      { q: "Besides a great army, what other ‘gift’ did Philip arrange for his son Alexander?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The tutor Aristotle", "A fleet of warships", "A treaty with Persia", "A new capital city"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Philip hired Aristotle to tutor the young Alexander — connecting this arc straight back to the last one." },
      { q: "How did Philip’s reign end?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He was assassinated in 336 BCE", "He died peacefully of old age", "He was defeated by Persia", "He gave up the throne"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He was struck down by an assassin at a royal wedding — and the 20-year-old Alexander inherited everything." },
      { q: "The deeper point of starting Alexander’s story with Philip is that —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Even the most dazzling success usually stands on a foundation someone else built", "Philip was a better general than Alexander", "Alexander invented the phalanx himself", "Macedon was always the strongest kingdom"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Alexander was a genius — but he inherited a finished war machine. Great achievements almost always rest on groundwork laid by others first." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — THE BOY WHO CONQUERED THE WORLD ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "alexrise", arc: "alexander", n: 2, minutes: 15,
    title: "Never a Single Defeat",
    hook: "He tamed a ‘wild’ horse no grown man could ride, cut through a puzzle no one could solve, and beat the largest empire on earth — all before he turned 30.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "A magnificent black horse rears and snorts; no one can mount it, and the king is ready to send it away. A boy of about twelve quietly notices what the grown men missed — the horse is terrified of its own shadow. He turns its head toward the sun so the shadow falls behind it, speaks softly, and swings up onto its back. The court goes silent.",
        note: "The horse is Bucephalus. Alexander will ride him into battle for the next twenty years, and name a city after him when he dies." },
      { t: "p", html: "Slow that famous moment down, because there’s a whole personality packed inside it. A dozen tough, experienced horsemen had wrestled with that animal and failed, and concluded the horse was simply wild and useless. A boy stood at the edge of the crowd and asked a different question: not ‘how do I overpower it?’ but ‘<i>what is it afraid of?</i>’ He had watched closely enough to spot that the horse panicked every time its own dark shadow jumped on the ground in front of it. Turn its face to the sun, and the terror — quite literally — fell behind it. That is the difference between forcing the world and understanding it, and Alexander, at twelve, already preferred the second." },
      { t: "p", html: "That’s the boy in a single story: fearless, but also <i>observant</i> — he won by seeing what others overlooked. When Alexander (<b>356–323 BCE</b>) took the throne at 20, he immediately pointed Philip’s army at the empire every Greek both feared and resented: <b>Persia</b>, the superpower of the age, ruled by King <b>Darius III</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s hard to overstate how reckless that decision should have been. Persia was not just another kingdom — it was the colossus of the world, vast beyond imagining, with more people, more gold, and far more soldiers than little Macedon could dream of. For a twenty-year-old to look at that giant and decide to <i>attack</i> it was the kind of thing that normally ends a young king’s reign in a single disastrous season. What made it work was that Alexander wasn’t bringing courage alone; he was bringing his father’s perfectly drilled war machine and his own uncanny eye for the enemy’s weak spot. Nerve plus preparation plus observation — the same three things that tamed the horse." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The Gordian knot", html: "At the town of Gordium sat a wagon tied with a knot so tangled that legend promised whoever undid it would rule all Asia. Alexander studied it, then simply drew his sword and <b>sliced it in half</b>. ‘Cutting the Gordian knot’ still means solving an impossible problem with one bold, unexpected stroke." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a sly lesson tucked in the knot story, and it’s not really about swords. Everyone before Alexander had assumed the puzzle had to be solved the obvious way — by patiently picking the tangle apart with your fingers. They were stuck because they’d accepted a rule no one had actually stated: ‘you must untie it.’ Alexander’s move was to question the rule itself. The prophecy only said the knot had to be <i>undone</i>; it never said how. Sometimes the genius isn’t in solving the problem everyone sees, but in noticing the invisible assumption that’s trapping everyone — and refusing to play by it." },
      { t: "p", html: "Battle after battle, the war machine worked exactly as Philip designed — phalanx pinning the enemy, Alexander himself leading the cavalry charge straight at the weak point. At <b>Gaugamela</b> in 331 BCE he shattered a Persian army many times the size of his own. Darius fled, and was soon dead. The mightiest empire on earth had fallen to a man not yet 26." },
      { t: "p", html: "How does a smaller army beat a much larger one, again and again? Not by being braver — both sides were brave. Alexander won because his force fought as a single coordinated body while the enemy, however huge, often fought as a loose crowd. He would let the bristling phalanx lock the enemy’s center in place, then personally lead a cavalry charge like a thrown spear, aimed at the one spot where breaking through would cause the most panic. Size is frightening, but a giant that can’t move together can be toppled by a smaller thing that can. He proved it over and over, and the world ran out of armies willing to test it." },
      { t: "aside", who: "Diogenes says", face: "barrel", html: "“He conquered Persia, Egypt, half of Asia — and still couldn’t sit still for an afternoon. Tell me again which of us was free.”" },
      { t: "p", html: "He kept going — into Egypt (where he founded <b>Alexandria</b>, a city that would become the brain of the ancient world), through what is now Iraq and Iran and Afghanistan, all the way to the edge of <b>India</b>. He fought in deserts and mountains and monsoon rain. And through all of it, the record held: not one defeat." },
      { t: "p", html: "Try to actually picture the distance, because the numbers go numb otherwise. These men marched, on foot, across an expanse of the world it would take you many hours to fly over today — over scorching deserts where the heat could kill, up icy mountain passes, through jungles thick with disease, season after season, year after year, farther and farther from everything they had ever called home. They could not phone their families or expect to ever see them again. Whatever you think of the conquest, the sheer physical endurance of that march is staggering, and it’s a big part of why soldiers, explorers, and dreamers have been hypnotized by Alexander’s story ever since." },
      { t: "p", html: "But carry one uneasy question with you out of this lesson, because the next one is built on it. A person who tames the untamable horse, cuts the uncuttable knot, and beats the unbeatable empire — who has, in plain fact, never once failed at anything he set out to do — learns a strange and dangerous lesson: that limits are for other people. Winning everything sounds like the happiest possible life. It can quietly become a kind of trap. We’ll watch that trap close around him in the very next lesson, where the same gifts that built the legend start to cost more than anyone bargained for." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why he still dazzles", html: "Alexander combined two things that rarely live in one person: raw courage at the front of a charge, and a cool, watching cleverness — the boy who noticed the shadow. That mix is why, 2,300 years later, generals still study his battles. But notice the question already forming: a man who can win <i>anything</i> — how does he ever decide he has enough?" },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "How did young Alexander calm the horse Bucephalus?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He turned it to face the sun so it couldn’t see its own shadow", "He fed it for a week", "He had it blindfolded", "He let an older soldier ride it first"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He noticed the horse feared its own shadow — and won by seeing what the grown men had missed." },
      { q: "Which empire did Alexander set out to conquer?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Persia", "Rome", "China", "Egypt alone"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Persia — the superpower of the age, ruled by Darius III." },
      { q: "To ‘cut the Gordian knot’ means to:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Solve an impossible problem with one bold stroke", "Tie a very strong rope", "Lose your temper", "Run away from a challenge"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Alexander sliced the legendary knot with his sword. The phrase now means a daring, unexpected solution." },
      { q: "At the battle of Gaugamela (331 BCE), Alexander —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Beat a much larger Persian army and sent Darius fleeing", "Was nearly defeated and retreated", "Made peace without fighting", "Lost his horse and the battle"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He shattered a far bigger Persian force, Darius fled, and the empire soon collapsed." },
      { q: "Which famous city did Alexander found in Egypt?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Alexandria", "Athens", "Babylon", "Rome"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Alexandria became one of the great cities of the ancient world — a center of learning for centuries." },
      { q: "Trickiest: what two rare qualities does the Bucephalus story say lived in Alexander at once?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Fearless courage AND sharp, patient observation", "Wealth AND laziness", "Cruelty AND cowardice", "Luck AND nothing else"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He charged at the front like a daredevil, but he also <i>noticed</i> what others missed — the shadow. That blend of nerve and watchfulness is why he kept winning." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — GENIUS AND ASHES ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "alexcost", arc: "alexander", n: 3, minutes: 15,
    title: "Genius and Ashes",
    hook: "This is the hard half of the story — the part the movies skip. The same brilliant man who founded cities also burned them, and killed a friend with his own hands. Greatness and wreckage, in one person.",
    beats: [
      { t: "lead", html: "It would be easy to tell Alexander’s story as pure triumph. It would also be dishonest. To really understand him, you have to look at the cost — clearly, without flinching and without pretending he was a monster either. He was both more impressive and more troubling than a hero or a villain." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is one of the most important skills the whole island is quietly trying to teach you, so it’s worth naming plainly. Our brains love simple stories — hero or villain, good guy or bad guy — because they’re easy to hold and easy to feel. Real people almost never fit them. The grown-up move is to resist the tug toward one tidy verdict and instead keep two true things in your head at the same time, even when they pull against each other. Alexander is the perfect test case, because the same man, the same week, could do something dazzling and something terrible." },
      { t: "p", html: "Early on, the Greek city of <b>Thebes</b> rebelled against him. Alexander’s answer was total: he destroyed the city almost completely and sold its survivors into slavery, as a warning to anyone else thinking of resisting. It worked. It was also a city, full of people, erased to make a point." },
      { t: "p", html: "Sit with the cold logic of it for a second, because that’s what makes it chilling rather than just sad. This wasn’t a blind rage; it was a <i>strategy</i>. By making one rebellious city into a horror story, Alexander frightened a dozen other cities into never daring to rebel at all. In the brutal accounting of conquest, it ‘worked’ — fewer wars later, because of the terror now. But every person in Thebes was a real human being with a life, and they were traded away as a message to strangers. When you hear that something ‘worked,’ it’s always worth asking the next question: worked for whom, and at whose expense?" },
      { t: "p", html: "After conquering Persia, in 330 BCE, he <b>burned Persepolis</b> — the Persians’ glittering ceremonial capital — to the ground. Whether it was cold revenge for an old Persian invasion of Greece or a drunken night that got out of hand, the result was the same: one of the most beautiful places in the world, gone in a night of fire." },
      { t: "scene", html: "Years into the campaign, far from home, at a feast heavy with wine, an old friend named <b>Cleitus</b> — a man who had once saved Alexander’s life in battle — argues with him and mocks him. Alexander, enraged and drunk, grabs a spear and kills him on the spot. The next morning, sober, he is said to have wept for days and refused to eat.",
        note: "The conqueror who could beat any enemy could not always beat his own temper. That, too, is part of the truth about him." },
      { t: "p", html: "This story is almost unbearable, and that’s exactly why it’s worth telling. Cleitus wasn’t an enemy — he was an old comrade who had once thrown himself between Alexander and a killing blow. He had literally kept Alexander alive. And in a single drunken, furious instant, Alexander took the life that had once saved his own. The grief that followed was real and crushing; this was not a man who felt nothing. But grief afterward doesn’t undo a spear. It’s a brutal reminder that power without self-control is its own kind of danger — that the hardest enemy any person faces is sometimes the one inside their own chest." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a Greek word your glossary knows for the thing creeping into him: <b>hubris</b> — the dangerous over-confidence that makes a person feel almost like a god. The farther Alexander went, the more he seemed to believe ordinary limits didn’t apply to him. The Greeks had warned about exactly this in story after story, and here it was, happening to their greatest conqueror." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here’s what makes the hubris so haunting. The Greeks didn’t just stumble into this idea — they had been telling cautionary tales about it for generations, story after story of brilliant people who flew too high, stopped believing the rules applied to them, and came crashing down. Alexander would have grown up on those very stories; Aristotle himself may have taught them to him. And yet knowing the warning did not save him from it. Success, it turns out, is its own slow trap: the more you win, the easier it becomes to believe you simply <i>can’t</i> lose — which is the precise moment a person stops listening to the people trying to keep them grounded." },
      { t: "p", html: "And his men felt it. They had marched for eight years and thousands of miles. In <b>326 BCE</b>, at a rain-swollen river in India, the army that had never refused him finally did. They would not take one more step east. Alexander sulked in his tent for days — but for once, the world’s most unstoppable man could not get his way. They turned back." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a strange tenderness in that ending. The undefeated conqueror, who had broken the greatest empire on earth, was finally stopped — not by a stronger enemy, not by a clever rival, but by the exhausted love of his own men, who simply could not bear to follow him any farther from home. They didn’t hate him; many would have died for him, and had. They were just <i>finished</i>. It’s the clearest proof in his whole story that no one, however gifted, is truly self-made or truly unstoppable. Even the mightiest man alive moved only as far as other tired human beings were willing to carry him." },
      { t: "p", html: "So how should you hold a person like this in your head? Not as a poster to worship, and not as a monster to boo. Hold him as a warning and a wonder at the same time. Admire the courage, the brilliance, the refusal to accept limits — those are real, and they’re worth learning from. And refuse to look away from the burned cities, the murdered friend, the thousands who died so that one man would never have to feel finished. The skill isn’t choosing which half is the ‘real’ Alexander. The skill is being honest enough to carry both halves at once, and wise enough to ask which parts of him you’d actually want in yourself." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "The honest takeaway", html: "Brilliance does not cancel cruelty, and cruelty does not erase brilliance — they can sit side by side in the same person, and a grown-up understanding of history holds <i>both</i>. The interesting question isn’t ‘hero or villain?’ It’s ‘what did his gifts build, what did they destroy, and what can <i>I</i> learn from each?’" },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What did Alexander do to the rebel city of Thebes?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Destroyed it almost completely as a warning", "Made it his capital", "Left it completely alone", "Gave it independence"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He erased the city and enslaved survivors — a brutal warning to anyone else considering rebellion." },
      { q: "Which Persian capital did Alexander burn down in 330 BCE?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Persepolis", "Athens", "Carthage", "Memphis"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Persepolis, the Persians’ ceremonial capital, was burned — whether by cold revenge or a drunken night gone wrong." },
      { q: "True or false: Alexander once killed his friend Cleitus in a drunken rage, then deeply regretted it.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 0, explain: "True — he speared Cleitus during a wine-soaked quarrel and reportedly wept for days afterward." },
      { q: "The Greek word ‘hubris’ describes Alexander’s growing —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Dangerous over-confidence, as if limits didn’t apply to him", "Fear of battle", "Generosity to enemies", "Skill with horses"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Hubris is overreaching pride. The farther he went, the more godlike and limitless he seemed to feel — exactly what Greek stories warned against." },
      { q: "What finally forced Alexander to stop and turn back in 326 BCE?", type: "mc",
        options: ["His own soldiers refused to march any farther", "A crushing defeat", "He fell seriously ill", "He achieved his final goal"],
        answer: 0, explain: "At a river in India, his exhausted army simply refused to go on. The undefeated conqueror was stopped by his own men, not an enemy." },
      { q: "The deepest one: this lesson argues the mature way to judge Alexander is to —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Hold his genius and his cruelty in view at the same time", "Decide he was purely a hero", "Decide he was purely a villain", "Ignore the parts that are uncomfortable"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Real history resists ‘hero or villain.’ The honest move is to weigh what his gifts built <i>and</i> what they destroyed — and learn from both." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — THE EMPIRE THAT VANISHED ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "alexempire", arc: "alexander", n: 4, minutes: 15,
    title: "The Empire That Vanished",
    hook: "He conquered the largest empire the world had ever seen. It fell apart almost the moment he died — and yet, strangely, his real victory came afterward, in a form he never planned.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "Babylon, 323 BCE. Alexander — not yet 33, undefeated, master of a third of the known world — burns with a sudden fever and, within days, is dead. His commanders crowd around the bed. ‘To whom do you leave the empire?’ they ask. His reported answer is a disaster waiting to happen: ‘To the strongest.’",
        note: "No clear heir. No plan. Just the largest empire on earth and a roomful of ambitious generals who had each commanded armies." },
      { t: "p", html: "There is something almost unbearably human in that deathbed scene. The man had spent his entire adult life seizing <i>more</i> — more land, more victories, more of everything — and he had been so busy conquering the future that he never paused to secure it. He left no grown son ready to rule, no clear plan, no will that settled who came next. The very restlessness that made him unstoppable in war made him careless about peace. And so the greatest conqueror of the age handed the largest empire on earth to four words — ‘to the strongest’ — which was really another way of saying: fight it out among yourselves." },
      { t: "p", html: "What followed was exactly what you’d fear. His generals — history calls them the <b>Successors</b> — turned on one another and fought for <i>decades</i>. Alexander’s wife and son were murdered in the scramble. The empire that took him a lifetime to build was carved into rival kingdoms within a generation. As a single empire, it simply <b>vanished</b>." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s grimly fitting, in a way. Alexander had spent his life teaching the world that the strong simply take what they want — that ambition plus an army is enough to reshape the map. His generals had watched him do it up close for years; they were his star pupils in exactly that lesson. So when he died with no clear heir and four careless words, they did precisely what their teacher had modeled: they reached for everything, by force, and let the weaker ones fall. A kingdom built on the idea that ‘might makes right’ has no defense against the next ambitious person who believes the very same thing. He had, without meaning to, taught his own empire how to tear itself apart." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s a hard, useful truth that <i>winning</i> and <i>holding</i> are two completely different skills. Conquering land is a sprint of daring and force; keeping a peaceful, lasting kingdom is a slow marathon of patience, fair laws, trusted heirs, and the willingness to stop. Alexander was perhaps the greatest sprinter who ever lived and showed almost no interest in the marathon. The moment his single guiding will was gone, there was nothing underneath to hold the pieces together — no shared idea, no agreed rules, just ambition. Empires built on one extraordinary person tend to die with that person." },
      { t: "p", html: "So was it all for nothing? Here’s the twist. Even as the <i>political</i> empire shattered, something deeper had spread and stuck. Everywhere Alexander had marched, Greek language, art, coins, and ideas had taken root and blended with Persian, Egyptian, and Indian cultures. Historians call this blended age the <b>Hellenistic</b> world, and it lasted for centuries." },
      { t: "p", html: "Picture how that blending actually felt on the ground, far from any battlefield. In a market in Egypt or Afghanistan, a merchant might now keep accounts in Greek, worship gods that were a mix of local and Greek, use coins stamped in the Greek style, and pass those habits to children who grew up thinking all of it was simply normal. Nobody ordered this; no general commanded ‘blend your cultures.’ It happened the way it always happens — through trade, marriage, curiosity, and daily life — once the roads were open and the peoples were in contact. The armies kicked the door open; ordinary people walked through it and started talking." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The brain of the ancient world", html: "His city <b>Alexandria</b>, in Egypt, grew a library that aimed to collect <i>every book on earth</i>. Scholars there measured the size of the planet, mapped the stars, and advanced mathematics and medicine. A city named for a conqueror became one of history’s greatest homes for <b>peaceful</b> knowledge." },
      { t: "p", html: "Linger on that beautiful irony. A city founded by a man of the sword became, within a few generations, the place where humanity did some of its gentlest and most lasting work — measuring the earth, charting the heavens, healing the sick, and gathering the world’s books under one roof. The soldiers who built it are mostly forgotten; the quiet scholars who came after are still taught in classrooms today. Alexandria is living proof that what a thing is <i>used</i> for can end up mattering far more than what it was originally <i>built</i> for." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a thread here that ties this whole arc back to the very first one. Remember the chain: Socrates taught Plato, Plato taught Aristotle, and Aristotle tutored the boy who became Alexander. Alexander then carried Greek thought across half the world — and where did so much of it settle and grow? In libraries and schools like the one at Alexandria, where people did exactly what Socrates and Aristotle had taught: ask questions, gather evidence, argue carefully, write it down. The conqueror’s armies opened the roads, but what traveled down those roads and survived was the habit of <i>thinking</i> the philosophers had started. The sword cleared the path; the ideas did the lasting." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s a strange, important lesson about what really lasts. Alexander wanted an empire that would carry his name forever, and that empire was gone in twenty years. What actually survived was the <i>mixing</i> — ideas crossing borders, cultures learning from one another. The armies vanished; the conversation they accidentally started kept going." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that quiet truth is the perfect bridge into this island’s final arc. You’ve just watched a man who wanted <i>more</i> until the very last breath — who could conquer anything and never once chose to stop. Now you’re going to travel east, to a different giant of the ancient world, and meet a ruler who started out exactly as hungry as Alexander… and then did the one thing Alexander never could. He looked at everything his power had won him, and he decided, on purpose, that it was enough. Same appetite. Opposite ending. Keep Alexander fresh in your mind — you’re about to meet his mirror." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "What endures", html: "Conquest is loud and fast and often doesn’t last. The quieter things — language, books, ideas, the blending of cultures — can outlive every empire that carried them. Alexander is remembered as much for the <b>libraries</b> that followed him as for the battles he won. That’s worth sitting with." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "How old was Alexander when he died, and where?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Not yet 33, in Babylon", "About 60, in Macedon", "45, in India", "20, in Egypt"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He died of a fever in Babylon in 323 BCE, not yet 33 years old." },
      { q: "Who did Alexander leave the empire to?", type: "mc",
        options: ["No clear heir — reportedly ‘to the strongest’", "His tutor Aristotle", "His son, who ruled in peace", "The city of Athens"],
        answer: 0, explain: "With no real plan, his vague answer set off a violent scramble among his generals." },
      { q: "What happened to the empire soon after his death?", type: "mc",
        options: ["His generals fought for decades and split it into rival kingdoms", "It grew even larger", "It became a peaceful republic", "Persia instantly reconquered all of it"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The ‘Successors’ turned on each other; within a generation the single empire had vanished." },
      { q: "What do historians call the blended Greek-and-Eastern age that spread in his wake?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The Hellenistic world", "The Roman Republic", "The Dark Ages", "The Bronze Age"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Greek ideas mixed with Persian, Egyptian, and Indian cultures for centuries — the Hellenistic world." },
      { q: "The great library that aimed to collect every book on earth was in:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Alexandria", "Sparta", "Babylon", "Thebes"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Alexandria in Egypt became a powerhouse of learning — math, astronomy, medicine — for centuries." },
      { q: "The deepest lesson of the arc’s ending is that —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Ideas and culture can outlast any empire built by force", "Conquest lasts forever", "Libraries are useless", "Alexander achieved nothing at all"],
        answer: 0, explain: "His empire vanished in 20 years; the spread of ideas it accidentally caused lasted for centuries. The quiet things outlived the loud ones." },
    ],
  });

  /* ============================================================
     ARC 3 — THE KING WHO WEPT  (Ashoka)
     ============================================================ */
  arc({
    id: "ashoka",
    name: "The King Who Wept",
    emoji: "🦁",
    color: "#9c3b2e", color2: "#5e2018",
    blurb: "Half a world from Greece, a ruthless emperor won the bloodiest victory of his life — looked at what he had done — and chose to lay down the sword. One of the great moral turns in human history.",
    intro: "While Greek thinkers argued in the agora, a different giant was rising in India: the Maurya Empire, the first to unite almost the whole subcontinent. Its most famous ruler, Ashoka, began as a conqueror as fierce as any in this island — and then did something almost no conqueror has ever done. He stopped, on purpose, out of conscience.",
    overview: [
      { t: "p", html: "This arc is the deliberate mirror of Alexander’s. Alexander wanted <i>more</i> until the day he died. Ashoka wanted more too — until a single battlefield broke his heart and remade him. Same hunger, opposite ending." },
      { t: "p", html: "You’ll meet the cunning advisor who built the empire from a spider’s patience, the war so terrible it changed a king’s soul, and the astonishing idea of a ruler who carved his own apology into <b>stone</b> for his people to read." },
    ],
    badge: { name: "The Conscience of a King", emoji: "🦁" },
    lessons: ["amaurya", "akalinga", "adharma"],

    review: [
      { q: "Who founded the Maurya Empire, with the help of a brilliant advisor?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Chandragupta Maurya", "Ashoka", "Alexander", "Darius"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Chandragupta Maurya founded the empire around 321 BCE, guided by his ruthless strategist, Chanakya." },
      { q: "Ashoka was Chandragupta’s —", type: "mc",
        options: ["Grandson", "Father", "Tutor", "Enemy"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Ashoka was Chandragupta’s grandson, who inherited and expanded the empire." },
      { q: "Which war changed Ashoka forever?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The conquest of Kalinga", "The Trojan War", "The war with Sparta", "The Gordian campaign"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The brutal conquest of Kalinga — with around 100,000 killed — filled him with horror and remorse." },
      { q: "True or false: after Kalinga, Ashoka celebrated and kept on conquering.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 1, explain: "False — the carnage broke his heart. He turned away from war and toward dharma: compassion and moral rule." },
      { q: "How did Ashoka share his new ideas with his huge empire?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He carved edicts onto rocks and pillars across the land", "He sent secret letters only to nobles", "He banned all writing", "He built a single temple"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He inscribed his ‘edicts’ — public messages about kindness, tolerance, and dharma — on rocks and pillars for ordinary people to read." },
      { q: "Which symbol from Ashoka’s empire is on the modern Indian flag and national emblem?", type: "mc",
        options: ["His four-lion capital and the wheel (chakra)", "A two-headed eagle", "A golden sun", "A coiled serpent"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The Lion Capital of Ashoka is India’s national emblem, and his wheel — the Ashoka Chakra — sits at the center of India’s flag." },
      { q: "The deepest one: why is Ashoka’s change considered so rare in all of history?", type: "mc",
        options: ["A victorious conqueror voluntarily chose conscience over more conquest", "He lost a war and had no choice", "He was forced to change by an enemy", "Every king did the same thing"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Most rulers stop only when they’re defeated. Ashoka stopped at the height of his power, by his own choice, because of what victory had cost. That’s what makes the turn so extraordinary." },
    ],

    debate: {
      id: "ashoka-vs-alex",
      tag: "Big question — argue BOTH sides",
      q: "Who was the greater ruler — Alexander, who never stopped conquering, or Ashoka, who chose to stop?",
      setup: "One built the largest empire of his age and never lost. The other won, then renounced war to rule by compassion. Make the strongest case for <i>each</i>. Notice what you think ‘greatness’ in a leader actually means.",
      a: { label: "Alexander", h: "Greatness as daring",
        body: "Alexander did the impossible — undefeated, tutored by Aristotle, spreading ideas across three continents. He pushed the limits of what one human could achieve, and the world he reshaped lasted for centuries." },
      b: { label: "Ashoka", h: "Greatness as wisdom",
        body: "Anyone can want more; almost no one with absolute power chooses to use less of it. Ashoka turned an empire away from war toward welfare, tolerance, and care for the weak — and is remembered for what he built in peace, not whom he beat." },
    },
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — THE SPIDER AND THE EMPIRE ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "amaurya", arc: "ashoka", n: 1, minutes: 15,
    title: "The Spider and the Empire",
    hook: "Before Ashoka could become history’s most famous repentant king, someone had to build the empire he would inherit. That someone learned his greatest lesson from watching a spider refuse to give up.",
    beats: [
      { t: "scene", html: "A young exile, beaten and on the run, hides in a hut and watches a spider try to climb to its web. It falls. It climbs. It falls again. Again and again — and at last it reaches the top. The young man, history says, takes the lesson straight to heart: he will fail and rise, fail and rise, until he holds an empire.",
        note: "The exile is Chandragupta. India, around 322 BCE. Within a few years he will rule almost the entire subcontinent." },
      { t: "p", html: "Stories like the spider survive for thousands of years because they capture something real in a shape you can hold. Whether the young man literally watched a spider that exact afternoon hardly matters; what matters is the idea pressed into the tale. Almost nobody reaches anything great in a single clean leap. The honest path is messy — try, fall, get up, fall again — and the only thing that separates the people who eventually arrive from the people who don’t is often nothing fancier than refusing to stay down. The spider isn’t talented. It’s just relentless. That was the lesson, and Chandragupta took it to heart." },
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Chandragupta Maurya</b> founded the <b>Maurya Empire</b> around 321 BCE — the first state to unite nearly all of India under one ruler. But he didn’t do it alone. Behind him stood one of history’s most brilliant and ruthless strategists: <b>Chanakya</b> (also called Kautilya), a sharp-eyed teacher who picked the talented nobody Chandragupta and schemed him onto a throne." },
      { t: "p", html: "That partnership is a fascinating shape that appears again and again in history: the bold young leader out front, and the brilliant, patient strategist behind him doing the thinking. Chanakya didn’t want the crown for himself; he wanted the right <i>person</i> to wear it, and he was willing to spend years scheming, teaching, and maneuvering to put a talented unknown on the throne. The face the world remembers is Chandragupta’s. But a great many empires, then and now, were really built by the quiet planner standing just out of the painting — the one who saw the whole board while everyone else watched the king." },
      { t: "fact", label: "The ancient book of power", html: "Chanakya wrote the <b>Arthashastra</b>, a startlingly hard-nosed manual on running a state — taxes, spies, law, war, and economics. It’s so coldly practical that people still compare it to the most famous books on power ever written. Chanakya believed a ruler should be wise and just <i>and</i> completely unsentimental about staying in charge." },
      { t: "p", html: "What makes the Arthashastra so striking is how little it pretends. It doesn’t wrap power in pretty words; it treats running a state almost like an engineering problem — here is how you fill the treasury, here is how you keep informed, here is how you handle a rival, here is how you survive. You don’t have to admire every cold instruction in it to recognize the mind behind it. Chanakya understood that good intentions alone don’t hold a kingdom together; you also need taxes that get collected, laws that get enforced, and a ruler clear-eyed enough to keep the whole thing standing. Wisdom without that hard-headedness, he believed, simply loses to those who have it." },
      { t: "p", html: "Together they built something enormous: a capital city, <b>Pataliputra</b>, that astonished foreign visitors; a standing army; roads; tax collectors; and a network of spies so the emperor always knew what was happening in his vast land. This was not a loose collection of towns. It was a real, organized empire — centuries before many others." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s easy to read past a word like ‘empire,’ so picture what it actually required. To rule a land that vast, you can’t simply conquer it once and walk away — the distances are too great, the regions too different. You need roads so armies and messages can move; you need officials who collect taxes honestly enough to pay for everything; you need courts so ordinary disputes don’t turn into private wars; you need a way for the ruler to <i>know</i> what’s happening a month’s journey away. The Mauryas built all of that machinery, and built it early. The flashy part is the conquest. The part that actually lasts is the plumbing." },
      { t: "p", html: "And that careful, unglamorous machinery is the secret reason this empire could become the stage for Ashoka’s famous change. Think about it: a ruler can only choose to be merciful, to build hospitals and roads and carve thoughtful messages across the land, if there is a working state underneath him to carry those choices out. A grand conscience needs a real government to act through, or it stays just a feeling in one man’s heart. Chandragupta and Chanakya built the body; Ashoka, a generation later, would give it a soul. Neither half works without the other — which is exactly why this arc starts with the spider and the plumbing, not with the king who wept." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s worth pausing to place this in the bigger story of the world you’ve been exploring. While the Greek thinkers of Arc 1 were arguing in the agora, and right around the time Alexander’s short-lived empire was breaking apart into squabbling pieces, here in India a different kind of giant was rising — one that would prove far more durable. Far from being some distant, separate world, the two stories even brushed against each other through trade and travel. The ancient world was more connected than we sometimes imagine, and the Maurya Empire was one of its true great powers, not a footnote to anyone else’s." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a famous story that, late in life, Chandragupta gave it all up — set down the crown and became a wandering monk, seeking peace instead of power. Whether or not every detail is true, it plants a seed for this whole arc: in this family, even the mightiest could one day decide that conquest was not the point of a life." },
      { t: "p", html: "Notice how neatly that story rhymes with the man who taught Chandragupta the spider’s lesson. Chanakya’s whole philosophy was about <i>seizing and holding</i> power without sentiment — and yet the dynasty he helped create would become famous, two generations later, for a king who chose to <i>let go</i> of power’s cruelest uses out of pure conscience. The grandfather is said to have walked away from the throne; the grandson would walk away from the sword. It’s as if this family kept circling the same enormous question from different directions: once you have all the power in the world, what is it actually <i>for</i>? Hold that question. It is the beating heart of the two lessons ahead." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why start here", html: "Great empires don’t appear by magic; someone organizes them — roads, laws, money, patience. Chanakya’s spider lesson is really about <b>persistence</b>: failing without quitting. Ashoka, two rulers later, would inherit this powerful machine — and face the question of what a person should actually <i>do</i> with that much power." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What did the young Chandragupta supposedly learn from watching a spider?", type: "mc",
        options: ["To keep trying after failing, until he succeeded", "To spin webs", "To hide from enemies forever", "That spiders are dangerous"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The spider fell and climbed again and again until it reached the top — a lesson in persistence he took to heart." },
      { q: "Chandragupta founded which empire, around 321 BCE?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The Maurya Empire", "The Persian Empire", "The Roman Empire", "The Greek Empire"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The Maurya Empire — the first to unite nearly all of the Indian subcontinent." },
      { q: "Who was Chanakya?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The brilliant, ruthless advisor who helped Chandragupta seize power", "A rival king", "Chandragupta’s son", "A Greek general"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Chanakya (Kautilya) was the strategist behind the throne and author of the Arthashastra." },
      { q: "The Arthashastra is best described as:", type: "mc",
        options: ["A hard-nosed manual on running a state", "A book of poems", "A map of India", "A religious hymn"],
        answer: 0, explain: "It coldly covers taxes, spies, law, war, and economics — practical statecraft, not sentiment." },
      { q: "What shows the Maurya state was a real, organized empire?", type: "mc",
        options: ["A capital city, standing army, roads, taxes, and a spy network", "A single small village", "No government at all", "Only a temple"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Pataliputra, an army, roads, tax collectors, and spies — the machinery of a genuine empire, very early in history." },
      { q: "Trickiest: the story of Chandragupta giving up his throne to become a monk plants which idea for this arc?", type: "mc",
        options: ["That even the mightiest might decide conquest isn’t the point of a life", "That kings can never change", "That monks make bad rulers", "That the empire was fake"],
        answer: 0, explain: "It foreshadows Ashoka: in this family, supreme power could be set aside for something the ruler judged to matter more." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — THE DAY THE RIVER RAN RED ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "akalinga", arc: "ashoka", n: 2, minutes: 15,
    title: "The Day the River Ran Red",
    hook: "He began as ‘Ashoka the Fierce,’ a conqueror with no reason to ever stop. Then he won the bloodiest battle of his life — and the victory destroyed something inside him, in the best possible way.",
    beats: [
      { t: "p", html: "<b>Ashoka</b> (ruled about <b>268–232 BCE</b>), Chandragupta’s grandson, inherited the great Maurya machine and, by some accounts, fought his way to the throne ruthlessly. Early on he earned a grim nickname — something like ‘Ashoka the Fierce.’ He had power, ambition, and an army that had rarely lost. He looked, in every way, like the next great conqueror." },
      { t: "p", html: "Hold that early picture firmly in your mind, because the whole power of this story depends on it. The Ashoka of these first years was not a gentle man waiting to be revealed. He was hard, ambitious, and by some accounts cruel — the kind of ruler who clears rivals out of his path and doesn’t lose sleep over it. If you had met him then, you would never have guessed what was coming. That gap — between the fierce young king at the start and the man he would become — is exactly what makes his turn one of the most astonishing in all of history. People genuinely <i>can</i> change, and he is the proof carved in stone." },
      { t: "p", html: "One region still stood outside his empire: <b>Kalinga</b>, a proud kingdom on India’s east coast. Around 261 BCE, Ashoka invaded to finish what his family had started. Kalinga fought back hard. And Ashoka won — completely, crushingly. By the measure of conquest, it was a total triumph." },
      { t: "p", html: "By every standard he had ever been taught to value, this was the high point of his life. He had taken the one proud land that had defied his family, smashed its resistance, and stitched the last missing piece into his empire. The maps were finally complete. A young Alexander, in the same spot, would likely have felt only triumph and started scanning the horizon for the next target. For most of human history, this is the part of the story where the conqueror throws a feast and orders a monument to himself. Ashoka was about to do something nobody expected." },
      { t: "scene", html: "The battle is over. Ashoka walks the field of his great victory. It is not glory he finds — it is a wasteland of bodies, burning villages, weeping survivors, a river said to run red. By his own later account, the war left roughly <b>100,000 dead</b> and many times that number ruined: orphaned, enslaved, driven from home.",
        note: "We know these numbers because of something unprecedented: Ashoka himself ordered them carved into stone, as a confession." },
      { t: "p", html: "What seems to have undone him was seeing it not as a number but as people. From a distance, ‘a hundred thousand dead’ is a statistic — too big for the mind to really feel. Up close, walking the actual field, it becomes a thousand small unbearable things: one child crying beside one fallen parent, one burned home that someone had built, one survivor staring at nothing. Ashoka could no longer hide behind the grand word ‘victory.’ He had to look at the price of it, face by face, and the grand word fell apart in his hands. That collapse of the comfortable abstraction is where his conscience woke up." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here is the moment the whole island has been building toward. Standing in the wreckage of his own success, Ashoka did not feel triumphant. He felt <b>horror</b>. The suffering he had caused crashed down on him, and he could not un-see it. The fierce king broke — and out of that breaking came a completely different man." },
      { t: "quote", html: "On conquering Kalinga, the Beloved of the Gods felt remorse… for the slaughter, death, and deportation are extremely grievous to him.", who: "From Ashoka’s own Rock Edict (paraphrased)" },
      { t: "p", html: "Think about how rare this is. History is full of conquerors who killed on this scale and felt <i>proud</i> — who built monuments to it. Ashoka had won. No enemy forced him to change. No defeat humbled him. He simply looked clearly at what victory actually cost in human lives, and decided he would never do it again." },
      { t: "p", html: "And consider the staggering courage of writing it <i>down</i>. A powerful ruler’s natural instinct is to control the story — to be remembered as glorious and strong, and to bury anything shameful. Ashoka did the opposite. He took the worst thing he had ever done and ordered it carved into public stone, in his own voice, for his own people and all the centuries after to read. Not ‘look how great I am,’ but ‘look what I did, and how deeply I regret it.’ Admitting you were wrong is hard enough whispered to a friend. He confessed it to history, on purpose, forever." },
      { t: "p", html: "It’s worth saying that this kind of change is hard precisely because nothing forced it. When life knocks a person flat — a defeat, a punishment, getting caught — changing afterward is partly just survival; you had no choice. Ashoka had every choice. He had won. He was at the height of his strength, surrounded by people ready to celebrate him, with a perfectly good tradition that said conquerors were <i>supposed</i> to feel proud. To turn away from all that, with no enemy pushing him and no disaster to blame, purely because his own conscience would not let him rest — that is change in its rarest and purest form. It came from the inside, where it’s hardest to find." },
      { t: "p", html: "There’s a quiet challenge tucked in here for any reader, and it has nothing to do with armies. Almost everyone, sooner or later, ‘wins’ something in a way that hurts another person — an argument pressed too far, a friend left out, a small cruelty that got us what we wanted. The easy move is to enjoy the win and never look too closely at the cost. Ashoka’s real greatness wasn’t that he conquered Kalinga; plenty of kings conquered things. It was that he <i>looked</i> — honestly, without excuses — at what his victory had actually done to other living people, and let what he saw change him. That part isn’t ancient at all. It’s available to you this week — the next time you ‘win’ something and feel that small, uncomfortable tug that says someone else paid for it." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "The pivot", html: "This is one of the great moral turns in all of history: not a villain punished, but a powerful man who <i>chose</i> conscience over more power, at the very peak of his strength. The courage here isn’t winning the battle. It’s being honest about what the battle really was — and changing because of it." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "What was Ashoka’s reputation early in his reign?", type: "mc",
        options: ["A fierce, ruthless conqueror", "A gentle peacemaker", "A quiet scholar", "A failed general"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He earned a grim nickname like ‘Ashoka the Fierce’ — power and ambition, with an army that rarely lost." },
      { q: "Which kingdom did Ashoka invade around 261 BCE?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Kalinga", "Sparta", "Persia", "Egypt"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Kalinga, a proud kingdom on India’s east coast, which fought back hard before he crushed it." },
      { q: "How did Ashoka feel after his total victory at Kalinga?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Horror and remorse at the suffering he had caused", "Pure joy and pride", "Bored and restless", "Nothing at all"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Walking the field of the dead, he felt overwhelming horror — and it changed him completely." },
      { q: "How do we actually know the scale of the Kalinga slaughter?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Ashoka had it carved into stone as a confession", "An enemy wrote it down", "It was a secret no one knew", "Modern guesses only"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Astonishingly, Ashoka himself recorded the death and suffering in his own public edicts — a king confessing in stone." },
      { q: "True or false: Ashoka changed because an enemy defeated and humbled him.", type: "tf",
        options: ["True", "False"],
        answer: 1, explain: "False — no one defeated him. He <i>won</i>, then chose to change because of what winning had cost." },
      { q: "The deepest one: what makes Ashoka’s remorse so historically rare?", type: "mc",
        options: ["A conqueror at the height of victory chose to stop, out of conscience", "He was the only king to ever win a battle", "He immediately lost his empire", "Remorse was common among ancient kings"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Plenty of conquerors killed on this scale and felt proud. Ashoka looked honestly at the cost and renounced war — by his own free choice, while still all-powerful." },
    ],
  });

  /* ---------------- LESSON — THE WORDS CARVED IN STONE ---------------- */
  lesson({
    id: "adharma", arc: "ashoka", n: 3, minutes: 15,
    title: "The Words Carved in Stone",
    hook: "Most kings build monuments to brag. Ashoka built monuments to <i>apologize</i> — and to teach his people how to be good to one another. Some of them are still standing 2,200 years later.",
    beats: [
      { t: "p", html: "After Kalinga, Ashoka embraced <b>Buddhism</b> and devoted his rule to <b>dharma</b> — a word that here means something like ‘the moral law,’ a life of compassion, honesty, and non-violence. But he didn’t just feel sorry privately. He set out to turn an entire empire toward kindness — and he needed a way to speak to millions of people who would never see his face." },
      { t: "p", html: "Here’s the genuinely hard part of his turn, the part that separates real change from a passing mood. It is one thing to feel sorry after a tragedy — almost anyone does, for a while. It is something else entirely to <i>rebuild your whole life and job</i> around that regret and keep it up for decades. Ashoka still had an empire to run; he couldn’t simply walk away into a forest. So he asked a question very few powerful people ever ask: now that I refuse to rule by terror, how do I actually use this enormous power for <i>good</i>? The rest of his reign was his long, practical answer." },
      { t: "p", html: "His solution was brilliant and completely new: he carved his messages — we call them <b>edicts</b> — onto giant rocks and tall polished stone pillars all across his empire, where ordinary travelers could read or be told them. Imagine a king today posting his deepest principles on billboards in every town, signed in his own name. That’s what Ashoka did, in stone, for keeps." },
      { t: "p", html: "And the choice of stone was itself a kind of message. He could have whispered his new ideals only to priests and nobles, the way rulers usually shared their thinking. Instead he aimed straight at the ordinary person — the farmer, the trader, the traveler resting on a long road — and chose the most durable material he could find, so the words would outlast him, outlast his children, outlast his whole dynasty. He was, in effect, speaking past the people of his own time to everyone who would ever pass that rock. We are reading those messages right now. That is exactly the audience he was reaching for." },
      { t: "fact", label: "What the edicts actually say", html: "Not ‘obey me’ or ‘fear me.’ They urge people to respect their parents, be kind to servants and animals, tell the truth, and — remarkably for the ancient world — to <b>tolerate other religions</b>. One edict says honoring your own faith while insulting someone else’s actually harms your own. That message is 2,200 years old." },
      { t: "p", html: "That last idea deserves to be read twice, because it is startlingly ahead of its time. In an age when kings routinely forced one religion on everyone and crushed the rest, here was the most powerful man in India writing, in stone, that you should <i>respect</i> other people’s beliefs — and arguing that tearing someone else’s faith down doesn’t lift your own up; it drags your own down with it. It’s a piece of wisdom the world is still struggling to fully learn more than two thousand years later. He didn’t demand that everyone believe the same things. He asked them to be decent to one another while believing different ones." },
      { t: "p", html: "And he backed words with deeds. Ashoka built <b>hospitals</b> (for people <i>and</i> animals), dug wells, planted shade trees along the roads, and set up rest houses for travelers. He sent teachers of Buddhism far beyond his borders — including, by tradition, his own son and daughter to Sri Lanka — which helped grow a small faith into one of the world’s great religions." },
      { t: "p", html: "That last point quietly outgrew anything his armies ever did. Before Ashoka, Buddhism was a relatively small teaching, known mostly in one corner of the world. By choosing to spread it through <i>persuasion</i> rather than conquest — sending teachers, not soldiers — he helped turn it into a faith that would one day be followed by hundreds of millions of people across many lands, and is still followed today. Stop and weigh that against everything you learned in the Alexander arc. Alexander spread his influence with the sword, and his empire vanished within twenty years. Ashoka spread his with kindness and an idea, and it lasted more than two thousand. The contrast practically writes itself." },
      { t: "p", html: "This is the test of whether someone’s fine words mean anything: do they cost the speaker anything? Ashoka’s did. Hospitals, wells, shade trees, rest houses for strangers — none of that is cheap, and none of it makes a king more feared or wins him more land. It’s the opposite of conquest: power spent quietly on the comfort of people who could never repay it, including travelers he would never meet and animals that could never thank him. A man who once measured himself by the territory he could take began, instead, to measure himself by the suffering he could ease. That is the whole turn, made real in roads and wells." },
      { t: "order", title: "Ashoka’s turn, in order", sub: "Drag these into the order they happened — earliest at the top.",
        items: [ { yr: "~268 BCE", label: "Ashoka becomes emperor — fierce and ambitious" },
                 { yr: "~261 BCE", label: "He conquers Kalinga — and is horrified by the cost" },
                 { yr: "after Kalinga", label: "He embraces Buddhism and rules by dharma" },
                 { yr: "for years after", label: "He carves edicts in stone and builds for his people" } ] },
      { t: "p", html: "His most famous monument is a sculpture of <b>four lions</b> standing back to back atop a pillar — the <b>Lion Capital</b>. Look closely at modern India and you’ll find it everywhere: those four lions are the country’s national emblem, and Ashoka’s <b>wheel</b> sits right in the center of India’s flag. A king who renounced war 2,200 years ago is woven into a living nation today." },
      { t: "p", html: "Pause on what that means. When India became a free nation in the modern world and had to choose the symbols it most wanted to stand for, it did not reach for a fearsome warrior or a famous conqueror. It reached back across more than two thousand years and chose the emblems of the king who is remembered above all for his <i>conscience</i> — the one who looked at his own cruelty and turned away from it. Of all the rulers in that long history, the one a billion people carry on their flag and their coins today is the one who learned to regret a war. That choice is its own quiet verdict on what kind of greatness lasts." },
      { t: "keyidea", tag: "Why he still matters", html: "Ashoka proves that the bravest thing a powerful person can do is sometimes to use <i>less</i> power, on purpose. Alexander is remembered for what he conquered; Ashoka, for what he chose not to. As you leave this arc, hold them up side by side — and ask yourself which kind of greatness you’d rather have." },
    ],
    quiz: [
      { q: "After Kalinga, Ashoka devoted his rule to ‘dharma.’ Here that means roughly:", type: "mc",
        options: ["A moral life of compassion, honesty, and non-violence", "Winning more wars", "Collecting more taxes", "Building bigger armies"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He embraced Buddhism and tried to rule by compassion and non-violence rather than force." },
      { q: "How did Ashoka share his message with millions of people?", type: "mc",
        options: ["He carved edicts onto rocks and pillars across the empire", "He mailed letters to each home", "He told only his generals", "He kept it all secret"],
        answer: 0, explain: "His edicts — public moral messages — were inscribed in stone where ordinary people could encounter them." },
      { q: "Which idea, remarkable for the ancient world, appears in Ashoka’s edicts?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Tolerance and respect for other religions", "Conquer your neighbors", "Pay no taxes", "Worship only the king"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He urged respecting other faiths — even saying that insulting another religion harms your own. Strikingly modern, 2,200 years ago." },
      { q: "Which of these did Ashoka actually build for ordinary people?", type: "mc",
        options: ["Hospitals, wells, shade trees, and rest houses", "Gladiator arenas", "A giant war fleet", "Pyramids"],
        answer: 0, explain: "He backed his words with welfare works — care for humans and animals alike." },
      { q: "Which symbol from Ashoka is part of modern India today?", type: "mc",
        options: ["The four-lion capital and the wheel on the flag", "A golden eagle", "A red dragon", "A silver crescent"],
        answer: 0, explain: "The Lion Capital is India’s national emblem, and the Ashoka Chakra (wheel) is at the center of the Indian flag." },
      { q: "The closing question of the arc asks you to compare Alexander and Ashoka. The cleanest contrast is:", type: "mc",
        options: ["Alexander is remembered for what he conquered; Ashoka for what he chose not to", "They were the same kind of ruler", "Neither one ever fought a war", "Ashoka conquered more land than Alexander"],
        answer: 0, explain: "Same hunger for power, opposite endings. One never stopped; the other chose to. That contrast is the heart of these two arcs." },
    ],
  });

})(SUNSWORD.CONTENT);
